{{Disputed|date=September 2009}} {{Original research|date=July 2016}}
[[Image:Ruqun.png|thumb|500px|right|Two traditional forms of ruqun (襦裙), a type of Han Chinese clothing worn primarily by women.]] '''''Ruqun''''' ([[wikt:襦裙|襦裙]]) is an item of traditional Chinese attire (''[[Hanfu]]'') primarily for women but also for men. It consists of a blouse ([[wikt:襦|襦]], ''ru'') and a wrap-around skirt ([[wikt:裙|裙]], ''qun; ''also called ''[[wikt:裳|裳]], chang''). It is the eldest type of hanfu which is said to have been worn by the legendary [[Yellow Emperor]],<ref>[[Wikisource:zh:周易/系辞下#第二章]]：黄帝、尧、舜垂衣裳而天下治</ref> and it is said to be worn by women since the [[Warring States period]].
==History== Ruqun is the most basic type of Hanfu. It is said to be the basic clothing up to the [[3 Sovereigns and 5 Emperors]] age. At that time, it was worn by both men and women.
Generally the blouse was tucked into the skirt. The popularity of ''ruqun'' declined during the [[Han Dynasty]]. Although the popularity of women wearing ''ruqun'' increased again during the [[Southern and Northern Dynasties]], most men did not wear it any more. In the [[Cao Wei|Wei Dynasty]] and [[Jin Dynasty (265–420)|Jin Dynasty]] ''ruqun'' went through a major change when women started to wear much longer upper garments which needed to be put out of the skirt.{{Dubious|date=May 2009}} This new style of ruqun was called ''shanqun (衫裙)'' and existed with ''ruqun.'' During the [[Sui Dynasty|Sui]] and [[Tang Dynasty]], the skirts were tied higher and higher up the waist, until they were eventually tied above the breasts, worn with short blouses. In addition to the normal crossed-collar blouses, parallel/straight-collar (對襟) blouses were also worn in this period, thus exposing the cleavage of the breasts. During the [[Song Dynasty]], the skirts were eventually lowered from the breast level back to the normal waistline. In the early [[Ming Dynasty]], ''ruqun''<nowiki/>'s variant, ''shanqun'', went through a major change when women stopped using the sash. This new style of ''ruqun'', also called ''aoqun'' (襖裙), became popular in the late [[Ming Dynasty]].{{Dubious|date=May 2009}}
==Late Imperial Era== By the Ming Dynasty, ''ruqun'' became the most common form of attire for women. The sleeves of the blouse are mostly curved with a narrow sleeve cuff (琵琶袖, ''[[pipa]]'' sleeve). The collar is of the same colour as the clothing. Often, there is an optional detachable protective ''huling'' (護領, lit. "protect collar") sewn to the collar. The ''huling'' can be white or any dark colour, and is used to protect the collar from being rotten by sweat, therefore to extend the life of the clothing. Towards the start of the [[Qing Dynasty]], the skirt was mostly ''baizhequn'' (百摺裙, lit. "hundred pleats skirt") or ''mamianqun'' (馬面裙, lit. "horse face skirt").{{Dubious|date=May 2009}}
<gallery> Image:Ruqun han.jpg|A Han Dynasty painting illustrates women wearing ''ruqun'', with blouses tucked into skirts Image:Court ladies pounding silk from a painting (捣练图) by Emperor Huizong.jpg|A Tang Dynasty painting illustrates women wearing ''ruqun'', with skirts tied above the breasts and short parallel-collar blouses Image:Tanghanfu.jpg|Another Tang Dynasty painting illustrating ''ruqun'' File:A palace concert.jpg|A Tang Dynasty palace concert wearing ''ruqun'' Image:Mingrenwu63.jpg|A painting by Ming Dynasty painter [[Tang Yin]] illustrating women in ''ruqun'' Image:Tangyin7big.jpg|A painting by Ming Dynasty painter [[Tang Yin]] illustrating women in ''ruqun'' Image:Mingrenwu65b.jpg|A painting by Ming Dynasty painter [[Tang Yin]] illustrating women in ''ruqun'' Image:Chujutu.jpg|Illustration of Ming Dynasty ''ruqun'' Image:Jiao_Bingzhen_-_Paintings_of_Ladies_-_Leaf_2.jpg|Illustration of Ruqun and Pifeng during Qing Dynasty </gallery>
==See also== *[[Xuanduan]] (玄端): a very formal dark ruqun with accessories; equivalent to the Western white tie * [[Han Chinese clothing]] *[[List of Han Chinese clothing]]
