{{Use British English|date=May 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}} {{Infobox person |name = Stephen Cobb |image = File:Formal_headshot_of_Stephen_Cobb.jpg |image_size = |caption = Cobb in 2012 |birth_name = |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1952|10|17}} |birth_place = Coventry, England |death_date = |death_place = |death_cause = |resting_place = |resting_place_coordinates = |residence = |nationality = U.S. |other_names = |known_for = |education = University of Leeds, University of Leicester, U.K. |alma_mater = |employer = [[ESET]] |occupation = [[Computer Security Professional, Author]] |home_town = [[Coventry]] |title = |salary = |networth = |height = |weight = |term = |predecessor = |successor = |party = |boards = CompTIA IT Security Executive Council, Board of Advisors - FHOOSH, |religion = |spouse = Chey |partner = |children = |parents = |relatives = Michael 'Mike' Cobb |signature = |website = [http://www.welivesecurity.com Computer security articles] |footnotes = }}
'''Stephen Cobb''' (born 17 October 1952 in [[Coventry]]) is an expert on [[internet security|security]], [[privacy]], and related topics.<ref>[http://readwrite.com/2013/03/08/12-things-you-probably-didnt-know-about-online-security/ ReadWrite interview at RSA]</ref>
Widely published as a technical author in the 1980s, Cobb became known for his efforts to educate consumers and companies in data privacy and information security. In 1996, Cobb became one of the first people to earn the Certified Information System Security Professional (CISSP) qualification. He later co-founded two information security startups, one of which developed innovative anti-spam technology that is still in use today (both firms were sold to NASDAQ listed companies).<ref>[http://ubiquity.acm.org/article.cfm?id=1149825 ACM Ubiquity, Volume 2006 Issue July]</ref> Cobb has been cited as an information security expert by national media and in congressional testimony.<ref>[https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CHRG-114hhrg94108/html/CHRG-114hhrg94108.htm Committee on Homeland Security, House Of Representatives, 114th Congress, 2/25/15]</ref>
==Written work== After authoring more than a dozen textbooks on how to use spreadsheets, databases, and other software applications, Cobb's first book on PC and LAN Security was published in 1991.<ref>[https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/search?searchType=7&searchId=22102&maxResultsPerPage=100&recCount=100&recPointer=0&resultPointer=0& Library of Congress]</ref> In 2002, Cobb published a primer on privacy for businesses.<ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/301361955_Privacy_for_Business_Web_sites_and_email Research Gate]</ref> As co-author and editor of the [[Trusted Email Open Standard]] Cobb helped present this proposal for securing email to the [[Federal Trade Commission]] in 2003. After a brief hiatus from privacy and security research, during which he produced an independent documentary on racial inequality in America ([[Dare Not Walk Alone]], 2006), Cobb co-authored a peer-reviewed paper on the dangers of malicious code use by governments, which he termed "righteous malware".<ref>[http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/articleDetails.jsp?arnumber=6916396&queryText=cycon%202014&pageNumber=2&newsearch=true Proceedings of CyCon 2014: 6th International Conference On Cyber Conflict]</ref> Cobb's historical analysis of cybercrime surveys was presented at Virus Bulletin 2015.<ref>[https://www.virusbulletin.com/blog/2016/02/vb2015-paper-sizing-cybercrime-incidents-and-accidents-hints-and-allegations/ Virus Bulletin, 2015]</ref>
==Entrepreneurial activities== Cobb co-founded two information security startups that were sold to NASDAQ listed companies. The first was InfoSec Labs, acquired in 1999 by [[Rainbow Technologies]], a maker of encryption products such as the CryptoSwift Hardware Security Module (HSM). The second was [[ePrivacy Group]], the company that created the [[TurnTide]] anti-spam technology.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100328113940/http://www.internetacceleration.com/newsletters/email-9-29-06.htm Internet Archive]</ref> This technology was acquired by [[Symantec]] in 2004 was still in use a decade later as the Symantec Traffic Shaper.<ref>[https://support.symantec.com/en_US/article.TECH123509.html Symantec]</ref>
==Security awareness and education== Cobb served for four years on the IT Security Executive Council of CompTIA (2012-2015). He frequently represents Security Our eCity, a non-profit community-wide security awareness organization based in San Diego.<ref>[http://securingourecity.org/the-new-and-expanded-cyber-boot-camp-2015 Securing Our eCity]</ref> In that role, he helped organize annual Cyber Boot Camps for middle school and high school students that have received national attention.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jun/19/business/la-fi-tn-young-cybersecurity-pros-reap-rewards-20130618 Los Angeles Times]</ref> Cobb has been an invited speaker on information security and data privacy issues in a dozen countries.<ref>[http://www.himssconference.org/speaker/stephen-cobb HIMSS Conference 2015]</ref> He is also a TEDx speaker.<ref>[http://www.tedxsandiego.com/videos/2015-videos/ TEDx San Diego 2015]</ref> As a security researcher with ESET, Cobb has tracked the effects of security breaches on economic activity. For example, in the wake of the [[Global surveillance disclosures (2013–present)|Snowden revelations]] he documented a drop in online shopping and banking.<ref>[https://blogs.wsj.com/cio/2014/04/03/post-snowden-some-internet-usage-is-contracting-study-finds/ Wall Street Journal]</ref> Cobb holds a master of science degree in security and risk management from the [[University of Leicester]] where his dissertation addressed aspects of the cybersecurity skills gap.<ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/project/Characteristics-of-effective-Chief-Information-Security-Officers-CISOs ResearchGate]</ref>
